 I could use `GitTagCommand.executeTagCommand` on an initialized repo, but I'm unsure if I need to test signed tags since that requires GPG configuration.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing tag command functionality**\\n\\nI’m exploring the new API that introduces `FORCE_NO_SIGN` with `--no-sign`, but I can't access command construction directly. The public `executeTagCommand` with `DEFAULT` creates a regular tag, and `FORCE_NO_SIGN` seems safe if the git version supports it. However, I’m debating whether I need to test the signed tag since existing tests use `-s`, and running those is difficult due to GPG. I might need to set up an initialized empty repo, commit files, and then call `executeTagCommand` to test tagging functionalities effectively.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating tag command assertions**\\n\\nI’m considering checking the success of tagging by listing files and asserting the git tag using `git tag --list` via an external process. It seems I may need an `ScmResult` for this functionality. To accomplish that, I’d direct the `createPushCommandLine` using the instance to keep the push argument construction intact. I also need to revise my imports — maybe `ScmTagParameters`, `TagScmResult`, and discuss if `SignOption` is necessary, especially if I’m avoiding deprecated APIs by setting `setSign(false)`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding method outcomes**\\n\\nI need to work with the SignOption, using either the default or FORCE_NO_SIGN settings. It's crucial to assert that the result is successful. The executeTagCommand returns a ScmResult, but the method also does. I'm wondering if I should use getSuccess to check this. I think it might help to review the ScmResult using javap to better understand its structure. It's all about making sure everything works together properly!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_D9l2OylVfZ5IlfkUNCqXhFzC|fc_00fba86f9b101280016a2a4f87ec388195ae94f339d24c4376", 